An interesting fragment a friend posted had its author bemoan society for reducing language to its bones, e.g. calling a place named "the Hall of the Imperial Lecture" a mere "lecture hall". Saying "trim it" instead of spelling out: "trim the lamp wick", always reducing, cutting.

Probably why longer names and phrases like: "The System of Pre-established Harmony", "Association-Induction Hypothesis", "The Human Instrumentality Project", "Intra-Uterine Paradesiac Locomotion" sound so alluring to us, the elegance of allowing ourselves not to rush with speech.

Dr. Ray Peat mentioned it, but a lot of pale people who have trouble tanning in summer seem to do better if they take a Vitamin D3 supplement for some time beforehand, a low blood Vitamin D level basically makes it harder to produce melanin because the body gets "greedy" for sun.

I've read that Vitiligo in black people is often related to a D deficiency too so it seems to make sense, D3 lack and hair loss is probably a similar relationship too. Anecdotally one patient I've seen with vitiligo was a farm laborer who spent all day outside so lots of factors.
